  "prompt": "What is the procedure of getting admission into IIT for NRIs?",
  "response": "The procedure for Non-Resident Indians (NRIs) to get admission into the Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) involves several steps. Here\u2019s a detailed guide to help NRIs navigate the process:\n\n### Step-by-Step Procedure:\n\n#### 1. **Eligibility Criteria:**\n   - **Academic Qualification:** NRIs need to have completed their 10+2 (or equivalent) education. The subjects should include Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics.\n   - **Age Limit:** There is no age limit for appearing in JEE (Advanced), which is the entrance exam required for IIT admission.\n\n#### 2. **Registering for JEE (Main):**\n   - NRIs must register for the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE) Main, which is the first stage of the IIT entrance process.\n   - You need to fill out the application form available on the National Testing Agency (NTA) website. Choose the 'NRI' category during registration.\n   - Pay the requisite application fee, which is higher for NRIs compared to Indian residents.\n\n#### 3. **Appearing for JEE (Main):**\n   - JEE (Main) is conducted twice a year, typically in January and April.\n   - You must score above the JEE (Main) cutoff to be eligible for JEE (Advanced).\n\n#### 4. **Registering for JEE (Advanced):**\n   - After qualifying JEE (Main), you need to register for JEE (Advanced).\n   - The registration for JEE (Advanced) is typically done on the official JEE (Advanced) website.\n   - You will need to provide your JEE (Main) roll number and other required documents.\n\n#### 5. **Appearing for JEE (Advanced):**\n   - JEE (Advanced) is generally held in May or June.\n   - This exam is more challenging than JEE (Main) and is the key to securing admission into IITs.\n\n#### 6. **JoSAA Counseling:**\n   - After the results of JEE (Advanced) are announced, successful candidates must participate in the Joint Seat Allocation Authority (JoSAA) counseling process.\n   - During counseling, you will need to fill in your choices of IITs and courses.\n   - Seats are allocated based on your rank, preferences, and availability.\n\n#### 7. **Document Verification and Admission:**\n   - If you are allotted a seat, you must complete the document verification process.\n   - Required documents typically include your 10th and 12th mark sheets, JEE (Main) and JEE (Advanced) admit cards and rank cards, passport, and proof of NRI status (like a copy of the passport of the sponsor and relationship certificate).\n   - Once your documents are verified, you can pay the admission fee and complete the admission process.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- **Preparation:** Start preparing early, as the competition is intense. You can use online resources, coaching centers, or self-study materials.\n- **Stay Updated:** Keep an eye on the official websites for JEE (Main), JEE (Advanced), and JoSAA for the latest updates and announcements.\n- **Financial Planning:** Consider the cost of education, including tuition fees, living expenses, and travel. Some IITs may offer scholarships or financial aid for NRIs.\n\nBy following these steps and preparing diligently, NRIs can successfully secure admission into an IIT.",
